[3] Sierra Leone: new case after 169 days
Date: Mon 14 Sep 2015
Source: Pulse [edited]
http://pulse.com.gh/international/after-169-days-young-girl-in-sierra-leone-diagnosed-with-ebola-id4166322.html


According to reports from BBC's Umaru Fofana in Freetown, Sierra Leone, a 16-year-old girl has been diagnosed with the deadly Ebola virus in northern Sierra Leone's Bomabli district, which had gone for 169 days without a case.

The initial suspicion is that the girl got Ebola after having sex with a survivor of the illness, but this has not yet been confirmed.

The survivor was discharged after being treated for Ebola in March [2015], according to DR Emmnauel Conteg, who is spearheading medical care for patients in Bombali.

He said 690 people in the entire village of Robuya, just outside Makeni city, had been quarantined with 7 "high risk contacts" taken to a treatment unit.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The girl died on Sun [13 Sep 2015] from Ebola virus disease. This is very disturbing since the Ebola survivor who is suspected of having sex with the girl had been discharged in March 2015. This adds to the growing body of evidence that the virus may survive longer than previously thought in semen, making the prospect of the country becoming Ebola-free in the immediate future more tenuous.

According to Reuters, in the nearby Kambia district on the border with Guinea, where nearly 1000 people are into their 2nd week of quarantine after the woman died, there is concern that a "high risk" contact remains on the loose, the head of Sierra Leone's Ebola response, Pallo Conteh said.

Both these events reinforce how fragile the current situation is. It will take very little to rekindle an outbreak. Until this last fatal case, transmission appeared to be under control with all contacts accounted for. - Mod.LK]

